# Ofiere Dashboard MCP Server — Implementation Plan

## Goal

Build a standalone MCP server that exposes **every feature** of the Ofiere dashboard as high-level, intention-driven tools. When installed by an OpenClaw agent, the agent gains full programmatic control over the dashboard — reading state, writing data, triggering actions — with the dashboard UI reacting in real-time via Supabase subscriptions.

## Architecture

```
OpenClaw Agent
     │
     ▼  MCP tool calls (JSON-RPC over stdio)
Ofiere Dashboard MCP Server  (standalone Node.js process)
     │
     ▼  reads / writes via Supabase JS SDK
Supabase (Postgres + Realtime)
     │
     ▼  real-time subscription
Dashboard UI (auto re-renders)
```

The MCP server is a **standalone Node.js/TypeScript package** that:
- Communicates with OpenClaw agents via **stdio** (standard MCP transport)
- Connects directly to **Supabase** using the service role key
- Requires **no dashboard process running** — it's independent
- Lives in a new directory: `dashboard-mcp/`

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Auth Strategy**: The MCP server will use the Supabase **service role key** to bypass RLS. This means agents have full access to all data for the configured user. The user's `user_id` will be set via environment variable `OFIERE_USER_ID` so all reads/writes are scoped correctly.

> [!WARNING]
> **Scope Decision**: This plan covers **70+ tools across 15 domains**. This is a large implementation. I recommend building it in phases (see Delivery Plan below). Please confirm if you want all phases or a specific subset first.

